AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - EUROPE (05): GERMANY (BRANDENBURG, SAXONY) WILD BOAR, SPREAD
**********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 22 Jan 2021 16:38 CET
Source: Saxon State Ministry for Social Affairs and Social Cohesion (SMS) press release [in German, machine trans., edited]
https://www.medienservice.sachsen.de/medien/news/245869


A further outbreak of African swine fever (ASF) was confirmed by the National Reference Laboratory at the Friedrich Loeffler Institute (Federal Research Institute for Animal Health; FLI) when a wild boar carcass was found in the district of Gorlitz. The location is in the existing buffer zone and is about 2 km (1.2 mi) west of the Rothenburg/Gorlitz airfield and about 3.5 km (2.2 mi) from the Neisse. Since this is south, i.e., outside of the previously endangered area, the restriction zones must be expanded. The expert group and the ASF crisis team of the SMS will meet shortly to coordinate this. The new restriction zones will be announced in the coming week in 2 general decrees from the State Office of Saxony. In addition, the ASF virus has been confirmed by FLI in a wild boar that was found near Skerbersdorf, approximately 80 meters (262 ft) from the Polish border. With these 2 new cases, the number of ASF-positive cases in Saxony increases to 19.

Minister of Social Affairs Petra Kopping explains: "The positive find is a boar that was found during the regular game hunt, which is carried out systematically in the buffer zone. The new find makes our fight against African swine fever more difficult. The epidemiological investigations have already started. First of all, we will draw a mobile electric fence around the location with a radius of 2 to 3 km (1.2 to 1.9 mi) to prevent any further infected animals from scattering. We will quickly adapt the existing endangered area and the buffer zone. It is positive that the previously endangered area is already completely closed with a permanent fence except for a few kilometers."

The 1st ASF outbreak in wild boar was officially recorded in the Free State of Saxony on 31 Oct 2020. With the new cases, a total of 19 wild boars were found positive for ASF.

African swine fever is a general contagious disease affecting pigs (domestic and wild boars), which is almost always fatal and incurable. There is no way to protect the pigs with preventive vaccination. The disease can be transmitted directly from animal to animal or indirectly via contaminated objects (clothing, shoes, vehicles) and food moved to other areas by humans. ASF is not contagious or dangerous for humans or other animal species.

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
